The paper discusses game theory and decision theory, which are both subfields of computer science. The focus on resource-bounded agents suggests that the paper may fall under the category of computational game theory (cs.GT) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of Turing machines and finite automata also suggests a connection to theoretical computer science, specifically algorithms and complexity (cs.DS) and automata and formal languages (cs.CC). Finally, the mention of modeling and algorithms suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.LG).
